{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513713"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:13:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:13:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12195"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12195"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.01,0.66,0.14,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4723"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66603"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4723"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12195"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52056"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1779"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2212"},{"type":"tags","id":"4378"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43300"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44590"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66603"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 31-year-old woman presents to the rural antenatal clinic at 22 weeks and two days gestation for review following a morphology scan showing an anterior low-lying placenta. She has had two previous pregnancies, both resulting in caesarean sections - the first emergency caesarean at 40 weeks and two days for fetal distress, and the second elective caesarean at 39 weeks and two days. She has no significant medical history and takes only a pregnancy multivitamin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender with a gravid uterus palpable at the umbilicus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immediate referral to maternal fetal medicine for repeat ultrasound scan","Magnetic resonance imaging at 28 weeks","Repeat ultrasound scan for placental location at 32 weeks","Serial ultrasound every two weeks for growth and placental location","Referral to maternal fetal medicine at 30 weeks for repeat ultrasound scan"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has significant risk factors for placenta accreta spectrum disorders, with a low-lying anterior placenta and two previous caesarean sections giving her up to a 11% risk of placenta accreta. Given this high risk, immediate specialist assessment is crucial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate referral to maternal fetal medicine for repeat ultrasound scan\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. Early diagnosis allows adequate time for delivery planning, including arranging appropriate resources such as blood products, interventional radiology, and a multidisciplinary surgical team. The scan should be performed by specialists experienced in diagnosing placenta accreta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging at 28 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E has similar diagnostic accuracy to expert ultrasound for placenta accreta but is more expensive and less readily available. While MRI may be useful as an adjunct investigation, it should not delay initial specialist assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound scan at 32 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would be too late for optimal planning if accreta is diagnosed, particularly in a rural setting where transfer to a tertiary centre may be needed. The high risk warrants earlier investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerial ultrasound every two weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive and unnecessary. A single detailed scan by specialists is more appropriate for diagnosis of placenta accreta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to maternal fetal medicine at 30 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E would delay diagnosis unnecessarily. Given the high risk of accreta and potential need for complex care planning, earlier referral is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWomen with placenta accreta typically require delivery by 34-36 weeks gestation at a tertiary centre with appropriate surgical and critical care facilities. Early diagnosis is therefore crucial to ensure optimal outcomes for both mother and baby.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Low-lying placenta with previous caesarean section significantly increases risk of placenta accreta spectrum disorders","Early diagnosis of placenta accreta is crucial for planning delivery and ensuring appropriate resources are available","Women with risk factors for placenta accreta should be referred promptly to a tertiary centre for specialist assessment","For women with placenta previa, the risk of placenta accreta is 3%, 11%, 40%, 61%, and 67%, for the first, second, third, fourth, and fifth or more cesarean, respectively"],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Placenta Accreta Spectrum (PAS): Consensus Guidelines [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Dec 1]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Placenta-Accreta-Spectrum.pdf","American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG). Placenta Accreta Spectrum [Internet]. Obstetric Care Consensus No. 7. Washington, DC: ACOG; 2018 Dec [cited 2024 Dec 1]. Available from: https://www.acog.org/clinical/clinical-guidance/obstetric-care-consensus/articles/2018/12/placenta-accreta-spectrum"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52056"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12195"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52056"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T15:01:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T15:17:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4723"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66603"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations",